item.title: Lawsuit Accusing Contractors of Paying Protection Money to Taliban Is Expanded
item.description: Families of American soldiers and personnel wounded or killed in Afghanistan have accused two U.S. contractors of paying protection money to the Taliban, expanding a lawsuit filed earlier.

item.title: OPEC, Allies Finalize Deal to Extend Oil-Output Cuts
item.description: OPEC and its allies finalized an extension of their record oil-production curbs through July, delegates said, after Iraq and Nigeria agreed to slightly deeper cuts to compensate for failing to adhere to recent agreements.

item.title: France Says It Killed a Top al Qaeda Chief in Africa
item.description: French military forces deployed in Mali killed al Qaeda’s North African commander, French government officials said, ending a decadeslong manhunt for an Islamic militant that Paris and other capitals blamed for scores of terrorist attacks and kidnappings.

item.title: Libyan Warlord, Facing Setbacks, Proposes Cease Fire
item.description: Libyan militia leader Khalifa Haftar proposed a cease fire and an Egyptian-backed process to end the war as the warlord’s forces lose swaths of territory gained in a 14-month offensive on Tripoli.

item.title: China Warns Citizens Not to Travel to Australia
item.description: The travel warning issued by China’s Ministry of Culture and Tourism represents a further fraying in relations between the two countries.

item.title: Protests Prompt Europe to Reckon With Racist Legacies of Colonial Past
item.description: Global protests over the killing of George Floyd are prompting some Europeans to confront their colonial past and rethink racist traditions.
